"id":"mk19_a_gm_s1",
"title":{
"__html":"High Value Care in Internal Medicine"
},
"titleNode":{
"type":"section-title",
"hlId":"2f546b",
"children":[
"High Value Care in Internal Medicine"
]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"section",
"id":"mk19_a_gm_s1_0",
"children":[
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"a56fbd",
"children":[
"The United States spends more on health care than all other developed nations; however, it has higher rates of medical care–related mortality and shorter life expectancy. In response to this apparent paradox, health policy organizations advocate implementing a high-value approach to patient care. High value care is individualized care that delivers proven benefits while minimizing risks and unnecessary costs; it eliminates wasteful health care habits, improves health outcomes, and avoids harms. Third-party payers, including Medicare, have implemented reimbursement models that reward high-quality, efficient care."
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"7e4c9f",
"children":[
"When determining the value of an intervention, clinicians should consider benefits before cost, because focusing primarily on cost might result in continuing low-cost interventions that provide no benefit or avoiding expensive but highly beneficial interventions. For example, some costly or risky interventions, such as screening colonoscopy, are considered high value, whereas some inexpensive and low-risk interventions, such as daily laboratory testing in hospitalized patients, represent low value care. Examples of high value and low value care are provided in ",
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"b",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
{
"type":"table-link",
"target":"mk19_a_gm_t01",
"wrapId":"1",
"children":[
"Table 1"
]
}
]
},
"."
]
},
{
"type":"inline-wrap",
"wrapId":"1",
"contentIds":[
"mk19_a_gm_t01"
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"711342",
"children":[
"High value care places patients and their outcomes, values, and concerns at the center of every major clinical decision and involves patients in decision making. Perceived patient demand is one important driver of inappropriate testing and treatment, and including patients in the decision-making process provides opportunities to educate them on balancing benefits with costs and to incorporate their values and preferences into the care plan."
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"afff0e",
"children":[
"Evidence-based decision support tools that consider value may assist physicians in providing high value care. In addition, the American College of Physicians offers resources to help clinicians determine the value of common tests and interventions (",
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"a",
"attrs":{
"href":"http://www.acponline.org/clinical-information/high-value-care",
"target":"_blank"
},
"children":[
"www.acponline.org/clinical-information/high-value-care"
]
},
"). The Choosing Wisely campaign, an initiative of the American Board of Internal Medicine Foundation with medical specialty societies, has published specialty-specific lists of commonly used tests or procedures whose necessity should be questioned and discussed by clinicians and patients (",
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"a",
"attrs":{
"href":"http://www.choosingwisely.org",
"target":"_blank"
},
"children":[
"www.choosingwisely.org"
]
},
"). Patient-friendly materials regarding these recommendations are available to consumers through a network of Choosing Wisely partners. Care coordination programs that focus on patients at risk for high-cost care also may facilitate the provision of high value care."
]
},
{
"type":"keypoints",
"children":[
{
"type":"keypoint",
"hlId":"681052",
"children":[
"High value care is individualized care that delivers proven benefits while minimizing risks and unnecessary costs."
]
}
]
}
]
